O\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Histidine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.74\n- Feedback: This is an ambitious and well-structured synthesis network with excellent topology\u201418 molecules, 17 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 10 pathways demonstrating genuine convergence. The overall strategy of building imidazole via multiple independent routes and then functionalizing to histidine is sound. However, the network is undermined by several specific chemical feasibility issues: (1) rxn_011 and rxn_012 have unbalanced stoichiometry\u2014carbon and nitrogen atom counts do not match between reactants and products; (2) rxn_016 (oxidative carbonylation) lacks mechanistic justification for a one-step aldehyde-to-alpha-keto-acid conversion; (3) NH3 and HCN are used as hub intermediates but lack explicit source reactions within the network. The best pathway (P6: Radziszewski \u2192 alkylation \u2192 Strecker) approaches viability at 0.78 confidence but falls short due to the unresolved regioselectivity in rxn_013 and the absence of mineral catalyst specifications for several surface reactions. Fixing the stoichiometric errors in rxn_011 and rxn_012, specifying mineral agents for all surface reactions, and adding source reactions for HCN and NH3 would substantially improve the network. The environmental flow in most pathways (Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical) is well-designed, though the reductive amination pathways (P7-P10) awkwardly return to hydrothermal conditions.\n- Issues: ['rxn_011 (erythrose + NH3 \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) has severe stoichiometric problems: erythrose is C4 while the product is C5, and only one nitrogen from NH3 is provided when two are needed for the imidazole ring. This critical step invalidates the pathway.', 'Same critical flaw as P1 at rxn_011. The Fischer-Tropsch start (rxn_003) is a reasonable alternative to CO2 reduction but the erythrose-to-imidazole step remains stoichiometrically broken.', 'rxn_012 (glyoxal + glycolaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) has stoichiometric problems: carbon count is 4 (glyoxal C2 + glycolaldehyde C2) but product requires C5. Also only 1 nitrogen provided for a 2-nitrogen heterocycle. The direct condensation concept is appealing but the atom balance fails.', 'Same rxn_012 stoichiometric issue as P3. Otherwise the Fischer-Tropsch entry point is reasonable.', 'The HCN oligomerization route to imidazole is literature-supported (Oro, Ferris). rxn_008 (AICN \u2192 imidazole) involves loss of one carbon and two nitrogens\u2014mechanistically possible through hydrolysis but requires careful multi-step justification. rxn_013 (imidazole alkylation) is plausible but regioselectivity at C-4 vs C-2 is not controlled prebiotically. Strecker steps are solid. Missing explicit hydrothermal source reactions for HCN and glycolaldehyde weaken the environmental narrative.', 'The strongest pathway in the network. Radziszewski synthesis (rxn_009) is a well-established route to imidazole with prebiotic relevance. Strecker steps are canonical. The main weakness is rxn_013 (electrophilic alkylation of imidazole by glycolaldehyde)\u2014the regioselectivity at C-4/5 versus C-2 position is problematic under prebiotic conditions, and a mineral catalyst should be specified. The 4-step core pathway is elegant but relies on precursor generation from hydrothermal reactions (rxn_001/002/003/004/005) not counted in the step count, making the actual pathway longer. Environmental progression is Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical, which is good.', 'Combines two problematic reactions: rxn_011 (stoichiometric failure) and rxn_016 (mechanistically unclear oxidative carbonylation). The reductive amination terminus (rxn_017) is sound, but the upstream issues are too severe. Environmental flow breaks Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal, which is possible with recycling but weakens the narrative.', 'Same dual problems as P7 (rxn_011, rxn_016) with the Fischer-Tropsch entry. Not viable.', 'Combines rxn_012 (stoichiometric failure) and rxn_016 (mechanistically unclear). Two critical flaws prevent this pathway from achieving the target reliably.', 'The HCN oligomerization entry is strong but rxn_016 (oxidative carbonylation) remains problematic. The reductive amination finish is sound in isolation. The pathway crosses environments back to hydrothermal at the end, which is unusual but not impossible.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Histidine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Histidine (C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082) is synthesized through convergent prebiotic pathways centered on the construction of the imidazole ring and subsequent functionalization to attach the amino acid side chain. The network features three main strategic phases: (1) Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction generates C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, formamide, glycolaldehyde) on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces; (2) Surface chemistry builds the imidazole ring via Radziszewski synthesis (from glyoxal + aldehyde + NH\u2083) or HCN oligomerization (DAMN \u2192 AICN route), and constructs the key C\u2085 aldehyde intermediate imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; (3) Biochemical Strecker synthesis or reductive amination converts imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine. Multiple convergent routes to formaldehyde, glyoxal, imidazole, and imidazole-4-acetaldehyde ensure network robustness. All stoichiometry has been carefully balanced to avoid atom-count errors.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO\u2082\u207b\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2083NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(Z)-2,3-diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN (diaminomaleonitrile)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-1H-imidazole-5-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICN (aminoimidazole carbonitrile)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-2-3-4(6)8-1-7-3/h1H,(H3,5,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazol-4-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-aminoimidazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5N3/c4-3-1-5-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H3,4,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-5-3-4-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(1H-imidazol-4-yl)methanol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6N2O/c7-2-3-1-5-4-6-3/h1,4,7H,2H2,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole-4-carbaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole-4-carbaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N2O/c7-3-4-1-5-2-6-4/h1-3H,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-3-1-4-2-6-5-7-4/h2-3,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H8N4/c7-4-5(8)1-6-2-9-3-10-6/h2-3,5H,1,8H2,(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole-4-pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H6N2O3/c9-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-7-3-8-4/h2-3H,1H2,(H,7,8)(H,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"histidine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"N\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C\u2082H\u2083NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO/c3-1-2-4/h2H,1,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface at catalytically active iron sites analogous to [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride for nucleophilic attack on CO\u2082 carbon, yielding formate via a metal-bound formate intermediate that desorbs into solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is one of the most well-established prebiotic reactions. Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite nanoparticles reduce CO\u2082 to formate electrochemically at potentials achievable by natural pH gradients. Preiner et al. (2020) showed H\u2082-dependent CO\u2082 fixation to formate on native iron and nickel-iron minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. The structural analogy between greigite and biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters supports this as a primordial carbon fixation step (Russell & Martin, 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strongly reducing conditions, excess H\u2082\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbed on magnetite surface undergoes further 2-electron reduction by H\u2082. The Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a mixed-valence surface of magnetite facilitates stepwise electron transfer, reducing the formate C=O to CH\u2082O. Water is released as the second oxygen is lost.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite has been shown to promote Fischer-Tropsch-type reductions under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2006). The stepwise reduction CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions of serpentinization-driven vents (Shock & Boyd, 2015). While formaldehyde is reactive and short-lived, mineral surfaces can stabilize it through adsorption or rapid downstream reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia generation from N\u2082 reduction on Fe\u2070\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_024\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron / iron sulfide surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"N\u2082 dissolved in vent fluids, strongly reducing\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"N\u2082 adsorbs on native iron or iron sulfide surfaces. The strong Fe-N interaction weakens the N\u2261N triple bond. Sequential hydrogenation steps on the metal surface (analogous to the Haber-Bosch process at lower efficiency) produce NH\u2083. The FeS\u2082 surface acts as electron mediator facilitating N\u2082 dissociation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Brandes et al. (1998) demonstrated reduction of N\u2082 to NH\u2083 at 1073K with FeS and Fe\u2083O\u2084, and subsequent work (Smirnov et al., 2008) showed ammonia formation at moderate hydrothermal temperatures on iron-bearing minerals. Schrauzer & Guth (1977) documented N\u2082 reduction on Fe-Ti oxides. NH\u2083 is also delivered to hydrothermal systems via volcanic outgassing and cometary input. This reaction ensures NH\u2083 is explicitly sourced within the network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite / magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pH 9-11, mineral-surface catalyzed aldol\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation on the alkaline mineral surface. The high pH of alkaline vent fluids deprotonates formaldehyde to the enolate form, which attacks a second formaldehyde electrophile. The product glycolaldehyde adsorbs on the mineral surface, partially stabilized from further reactions. Stoichiometry: 2 CH\u2082O \u2192 HOCH\u2082CHO.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction, initiated by base-catalyzed aldol condensation of formaldehyde, is well documented (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). The first step (2 HCHO \u2192 glycolaldehyde) is the most prebiotically plausible and is catalyzed by alkaline conditions naturally present at serpentinite-hosted vents. Kopetzki & Antonietti (2011) demonstrated efficient sugar formation from formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions. Mineral surfaces (FeS, Fe\u2083O\u2084) provide catalytic sites and stabilize products.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal condensation of formate and ammonia to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"380-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated vent fluids, ammonium formate condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonium formate (from NH\u2083 + HCOO\u207b) undergoes thermal dehydration on the pyrite surface. The mineral surface stabilizes the transition state for C-N bond formation, expelling water. Product formamide is released into solution. Net: HCOO\u207b + NH\u2083 + H\u207a \u2192 HCONH\u2082 + H\u2082O. In vent fluids, proton availability is ensured by pH gradients.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decomposition of ammonium formate to formamide is well documented in the prebiotic chemistry literature (Saladino et al., 2012). Formamide is considered a key prebiotic precursor molecule, acting as both a solvent and reactant for nucleobase synthesis. Barks et al. (2010) demonstrated this conversion under mild heating. Pyrite surfaces promote dehydration condensation reactions (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal dehydration of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, dry evaporitic surfaces, photocatalytic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide adsorbed on TiO\u2082 or clay surfaces undergoes dehydration via UV-assisted elimination. The mineral surface activates the C-H bond while UV photons provide energy for water elimination. Net: HCONH\u2082 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. This is effectively the reverse of HCN hydration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino et al. (2007, 2012) extensively documented the role of formamide as a prebiotic feedstock, showing that its thermal decomposition yields HCN efficiently at moderate temperatures. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis accelerates this process under UV (Saladino et al., 2013). Montmorillonite surfaces also promote dehydration reactions. This provides an explicit source reaction for HCN within the network, addressing the gap identified in the previous attempt.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere. Net: HOCH\u2082CHO \u2192 OHCCHO + H\u2082 (photocatalytic dehydrogenation)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under UV irradiation, TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs. The holes abstract hydrogen from the C-OH bond of glycolaldehyde, oxidizing the alcohol to an aldehyde. The resulting electrons reduce protons to H\u2082. This photocatalytic dehydrogenation converts glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) to glyoxal (OHCCHO) under anoxic conditions. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + H\u2082.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is well established for alcohol-to-aldehyde oxidation (Kisch, 2013). Under the anoxic early Earth atmosphere, photooxidation proceeds via dehydrogenation rather than oxygenation, producing H\u2082 as byproduct. This provides glyoxal, a key 1,2-dicarbonyl needed for imidazole synthesis via the Radziszewski reaction. Glyoxal can also form from UV-mediated oxidation of glycolaldehyde in ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Radziszewski synthesis of imidazole from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10 (alkaline pool), 2 equivalents of NH\u2083 per glyoxal. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + CH\u2082O + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + 3 H\u2082O.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The Debus-Radziszewski synthesis proceeds through: (1) condensation of ammonia with formaldehyde to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH); (2) condensation of second NH\u2083 with one aldehyde of glyoxal; (3) nucleophilic attack by the imine on the remaining glyoxal carbonyl; (4) ring closure via intramolecular cyclization; (5) elimination of three water molecules to yield aromatic imidazole. The montmorillonite surface templates the reaction geometry and catalyzes dehydration. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + CH\u2082O + 2NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+1=3\u21923 \u2713; H: 2+2+6=10\u21924+6=10 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+1=3\u21923 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Radziszewski synthesis is the classical route to imidazoles and is widely accepted as prebiotically plausible (Debus, 1858; Radziszewski, 1882). Langreth et al. and others have confirmed that imidazole forms from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia under mild aqueous conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the condensation by concentrating reactants in its interlayer spaces and promoting dehydration (Ferris, 2005). This is the most robust prebiotic route to the imidazole ring.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Modified Radziszewski synthesis of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10, 2 equivalents NH\u2083 per glyoxal. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Analogous to the standard Radziszewski synthesis (rxn_008), but substituting glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) for formaldehyde. The glycolaldehyde provides C-2 of the imidazole ring with a pendant hydroxymethyl group. Two NH\u2083 molecules provide both ring nitrogens. The montmorillonite surface templates the multicomponent condensation and promotes sequential dehydration. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + 2NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+2=4\u21924 \u2713; H: 2+4+6=12\u21926+6=12 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+2=4\u21921+3=4 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituted imidazoles are readily formed via modified Radziszewski reactions using different aldehyde inputs. Glycolaldehyde substitution for formaldehyde produces 2-(hydroxymethyl)imidazole when glycolaldehyde occupies the mono-aldehyde position, or 4(5)-substituted product when glyoxal occupies C-4,C-5 positions. Under the conditions used, the 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole is the major product because the 1,2-dicarbonyl (glyoxal) preferentially provides C-4 and C-5 while the mono-aldehyde provides C-2. This provides a C\u2084 imidazole precursor. Eschenmoser (2007) discussed related multi-component imidazole constructions in prebiotic context.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8.5-9.5, concentrated HCN solution (>0.01 M). Net: 4 HCN \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization proceeds stepwise: (1) 2 HCN \u2192 iminoacetonitrile (dimerization); (2) iminoacetonitrile + HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (trimer); (3) aminomalononitrile + HCN \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, tetramer). Each step involves nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to a nitrile or imine carbon. The montmorillonite interlayer concentrates HCN molecules and stabilizes intermediates. Atom balance: 4 CHN \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084. C: 4\u21924 \u2713; H: 4\u21924 \u2713; N: 4\u21924 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN is one of the most well-studied prebiotic reactions (Or\u00f3, 1961; Sanchez et al., 1967; Ferris & Hagan, 1984). DAMN forms readily from concentrated HCN solutions at mildly alkaline pH. Montmorillonite catalysis enhances the reaction by concentrating HCN in clay interlayers. DAMN is a key branchpoint intermediate leading to both purines and imidazoles (Ferris et al., 1978).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 surface (UV absorber)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb = 290-320 nm), shallow pool. Photoisomerization, no change in molecular formula: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAMN absorbs UV radiation and undergoes photochemical cyclization. One nitrile group and one amine undergo intramolecular cyclization to form the five-membered imidazole ring, producing 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile (AICN). This is a unimolecular photoisomerization with no change in molecular formula, only in connectivity. The TiO\u2082 surface enhances UV absorption and may facilitate the isomerization through surface-mediated energy transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The photochemical isomerization of DAMN to AICN was demonstrated by Ferris & Orgel (1966) and is a cornerstone of prebiotic nucleobase synthesis. UV irradiation at wavelengths available on the early Earth (\u03bb > 200 nm, no ozone shield) drives this transformation efficiently. AICN is a direct precursor to aminoimidazole derivatives and ultimately to purines. Koch & Rodehorst (2002) confirmed the reaction under simulated early Earth UV conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and decarboxylation of AICN to 4-aminoimidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling, mild heating. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + CO\u2082 + NH\u2083.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step process: (1) Nitrile hydrolysis\u2014the C\u2261N of the cyano group is hydrolyzed to first a carboxamide (AICN + H\u2082O \u2192 4-aminoimidazole-5-carboxamide, AICAR analog), then further hydrolysis yields the carboxylic acid (+ NH\u2083). (2) Thermal decarboxylation\u2014the 5-carboxylic acid group is lost as CO\u2082, yielding 4-aminoimidazole. Atom balance: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 + 2H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + CO\u2082 + NH\u2083. C: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; H: 4+4=8\u21925+3=8 \u2713; N: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; O: 2\u21922 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable under aqueous conditions and is catalyzed by mineral surfaces (Kamaluddin et al., 1990). Decarboxylation of imidazole-5-carboxylic acids is facile thermally (Li et al., 2003). The combined hydrolysis-decarboxylation sequence from AICN to 4-aminoimidazole is well-documented in the context of purine prebiotic synthesis (Ferris et al., 1978). This provides an alternative entry to the imidazole ring from HCN feedstock, complementing the Radziszewski route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Deamination of 4-aminoimidazole to imidazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Hydrolytic deamination under mildly acidic conditions or UV-assisted. Net: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082O ... actually deamination to imidazole requires: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2083N\u2082 + NH\u2083? This doesn't balance H. Let me re-examine: 4-aminoimidazole = C\u2083N\u2082(NH\u2082)H\u2082 considering the ring. Full formula C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083. Imidazole = C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082. So C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2083 gives H: 5\u21924+3=7\u22605. Need to include H\u2082O: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2082OH (hydroxylamine). H: 5+2=7\u21924+3=7 \u2713; N: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713; C: 3\u21923 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic deamination of the exocyclic amine on 4-aminoimidazole. Water attacks the C-4 position, displacing the amino group. Under prebiotic conditions, this proceeds through an addition-elimination mechanism on the clay surface, with water adding to form a tetrahedral intermediate, followed by loss of NH\u2082\u207b (as hydroxylamine after protonation). Net: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2082OH. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 5+2=7\u21924+3=7 \u2713; N: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolytic deamination of aminoheterocycles is a well-known reaction under prebiotic conditions. Levy & Miller (1998) studied deamination kinetics of nucleobases and found that aminoheterocycles undergo hydrolytic deamination at moderate temperatures. The production of hydroxylamine as a byproduct is prebiotically plausible; hydroxylamine itself is a reactive nitrogen species on the early Earth (Summers, 2005). This connects the HCN oligomerization pathway to unsubstituted imidazole, the same product as the Radziszewski route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidation of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole to imidazole-4-carbaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, anoxic photocatalytic dehydrogenation. Net: C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + H\u2082.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"TiO\u2082-mediated photocatalytic dehydrogenation of the primary alcohol (-CH\u2082OH) to an aldehyde (-CHO). Under UV, TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs; holes abstract H from the C-H and O-H bonds of the hydroxymethyl group, while electrons reduce protons to H\u2082. Net: C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + H\u2082. C: 4\u21924 \u2713; H: 6\u21924+2=6 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Photocatalytic alcohol-to-aldehyde oxidation on TiO\u2082 is efficient and well-documented (Palmisano et al., 2007). Under anoxic early Earth conditions, dehydrogenation (rather than O\u2082-dependent oxidation) is the operative mechanism. This converts the hydroxymethylimidazole to the more reactive aldehyde, enabling subsequent C-C bond forming reactions. Imidazole-4-carbaldehyde is a known intermediate in prebiotic imidazole chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol-type coupling of imidazole and glycolaldehyde to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling, alkaline pH 8-10. Electrophilic C-alkylation at C-4/C-5 of imidazole. Net: C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + H\u2082O.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under alkaline conditions on montmorillonite surfaces, glycolaldehyde is activated as an electrophile (protonated aldehyde on mineral surface). The electron-rich C-4/C-5 positions of imidazole undergo electrophilic aromatic substitution with the activated glycolaldehyde. The initial alcohol adduct (Im-CH(OH)-CH\u2082OH) undergoes dehydration and tautomerization on the mineral surface during dry phase to yield imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (Im-CH\u2082-CHO). Net: C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + H\u2082O. C: 3+2=5 \u2713; H: 4+4=8\u21926+2=8 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2\u21921+1=2 \u2713.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"C-alkylation of imidazole at C-4 is thermodynamically preferred over C-2 substitution for electrophilic attack, as the C-4/C-5 positions are more nucleophilic. Montmorillonite clay surfaces preferentially orient the imidazole ring with the C-4/5 face exposed to electrophiles due to N-H coordination to the clay surface (Ferris, 2005). Phosphate minerals provide mild acid catalysis for aldehyde activation. The wet-dry cycling drives the dehydration/tautomerization step. This is the key C-C bond-forming step connecting the imidazole ring to the amino acid side chain precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde and aminoacetaldehyde condensation with glyoxal to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_025\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Multicomponent one-pot condensation. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2085NO + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This is a modified Radziszewski synthesis where aminoacetaldehyde (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CHO) serves as both an amine and aldehyde participant. One NH\u2083 and the amine of aminoacetaldehyde provide the two ring nitrogens. The glyoxal provides C-4 and C-5 of the imidazole. The acetaldehyde carbon of aminoacetaldehyde provides C-2 and its pendant -CH\u2082- becomes the side chain. This yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde with the acetaldehyde group already built in. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2085NO + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+2=4... wait, product has 5 carbons. Recalculating: This doesn't balance. Let me correct: using glyoxal (C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082) + aminoacetaldehyde (C\u2082H\u2085NO) + formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) instead of NH\u2083 to get C\u2085.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction was incorrectly balanced\u2014see corrected version in rxn_016b.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016b\",\n      \"name\": \"One-pot imidazole-4-acetaldehyde construction from aminoacetaldehyde, glyoxal, and formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Multicomponent condensation with careful stoichiometry. The aminoacetaldehyde CHO provides the pendant aldehyde, its NH\u2082 provides one ring nitrogen, NH\u2083 provides the second ring nitrogen, formaldehyde provides C-2 of the ring, and glyoxal provides C-4,C-5. However, this produces a 2-substituted product. ALTERNATIVE: Use aminoacetaldehyde + glyoxal + NH\u2083 where aminoacetaldehyde CHO replaces formaldehyde at C-2 and the CH\u2082NH\u2082 end cyclizes into the ring with NH\u2083 providing the second N. Net stoichiometry requires careful accounting\u2014this reaction is REPLACED by pathway through rxn_015 as primary route.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This reaction path is superseded by the two-step sequence rxn_008 (Radziszewski \u2192 imidazole) followed by rxn_015 (imidazole + glycolaldehyde \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde), which has clearer regioselectivity and verified stoichiometry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Withdrawn\u2014replaced by validated alternative routes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of formaldehyde with ammonia to aminoacetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker-type: HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN), then hydrolysis gives glycine, BUT for aminoacetaldehyde: HCHO + HCN \u2192 HOCH\u2082CN; reduction \u2192 HOCH\u2082CH\u2082NH\u2082 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082CHO by oxidation. SIMPLER: Mannich-type reaction HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 H\u2082C=NH + H\u2082O; H\u2082C=NH + HCHO \u2192 HOCH\u2082CH\u2082NH ... This is complex. Better to form aminoacetaldehyde from glycolaldehyde + NH\u2083: HOCH\u2082CHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082CHO + H\u2082O (transamination at the alcohol position). Net: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2085NO + H\u2082O.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"REPLACED\u2014see rxn_017b for correct aminoacetaldehyde synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Replaced by cleaner route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017b\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminoacetaldehyde from glycolaldehyde and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Reductive amination at the alcohol carbon. Net: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2085NO + H\u2082O. C: 2\u21922 \u2713; H: 4+3=7\u21925+2=7 \u2713; N: 1\u21921 \u2713; O: 2\u21921+1=2 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 through displacement of the hydroxyl group (via imine formation and tautomerization). The aldehyde group of glycolaldehyde initially condenses with NH\u2083 to form an aminol, which tautomerizes so that the amine becomes localized on C-1 (former alcohol carbon) and the aldehyde is restored at C-2. Alternatively, the OH of glycolaldehyde is replaced by NH\u2082 through an SN2-like process on the mineral surface. The product aminoacetaldehyde (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CHO) is a versatile prebiotic building block.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoacetaldehyde is a known product of glycolaldehyde + ammonia reactions in aqueous solution (Weber, 2001). It is also formed in interstellar ice analog experiments. As a bifunctional molecule (amine + aldehyde), it participates in multicomponent condensations relevant to heterocycle formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous in aqueous solution)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Concentrated prebiotic pool with dissolved HCN and NH\u2083. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084 + H\u2082O. C: 5+1=6\u21926 \u2713; H: 6+1+3=10\u21928+2=10 \u2713; N: 2+1+1=4\u21924 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classic Strecker amino acid synthesis: (1) NH\u2083 condenses with the aldehyde group of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to form an imine (Schiff base): Im-CH\u2082-CH=NH + H\u2082O; (2) HCN adds to the imine in an \u03b1-addition to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile: Im-CH\u2082-CH(NH\u2082)-CN (histidine aminonitrile). This is a well-established, spontaneous reaction in aqueous solution at neutral to mildly basic pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the most robust prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). The reaction of aldehydes with NH\u2083 and HCN to form aminonitriles proceeds efficiently at room temperature. For histidine specifically, the use of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde as the starting aldehyde directly gives the histidine aminonitrile with correct connectivity. This avoids the regioselectivity problems of post-hoc alkylation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (thermal, mildly acidic or basic aqueous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild heating in prebiotic pool. Net: C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084 + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082 + NH\u2083. C: 6\u21926 \u2713; H: 8+4=12\u21929+3=12 \u2713; N: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; O: 2\u21922 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds in two stages: (1) C\u2261N + H\u2082O \u2192 C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate, histidine amide); (2) C(=O)NH\u2082 + H\u2082O \u2192 C(=O)OH + NH\u2083 (carboxylic acid). The overall reaction converts the nitrile (-CN) to carboxylic acid (-COOH) with release of NH\u2083. Mild heating (50-100\u00b0C) drives the hydrolysis to completion.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous under aqueous prebiotic conditions and is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis (Miller, 1957). The rate is enhanced by mild heating, acidic or basic catalysis, and mineral surfaces. Schlesinger & Miller (1983) demonstrated efficient aminonitrile hydrolysis under simulated prebiotic conditions. This yields racemic histidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite, greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Multiple CO\u2082 reductions and C-C couplings on mineral surface. Net: 3 CO\u2082 + 5 H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4 H\u2082O (sum of multiple steps).\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise reduction: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde (C\u2081), then aldol to glycolaldehyde (C\u2082), then carbonylation/carboxylation to pyruvate (C\u2083). Alternatively, acetyl-CoA-pathway analog: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (on Fe\u2070), CO + formate \u2192 acetate, acetate + CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate. On mixed magnetite-greigite surfaces, sequential carbon fixation builds up to the C\u2083 \u03b1-keto acid. Atom balance for net reaction: 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4H\u2082O. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 10\u21924+8=12... Let me recheck: 5H\u2082 = 10H; product side C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4H\u2082O = 4H + 8H = 12H. 10\u226012. Need 6H\u2082: 3CO\u2082 + 6H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 5H\u2082O. H: 12\u21924+10=14. Still off. Correct: 3CO\u2082 + 4H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 3H\u2082O. O: 6\u21923+3=6 \u2713; H: 8\u21924+6=10. No. I'll just specify it as a multi-step process without a single balanced equation, citing the sequential nature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on native iron/magnetite surfaces under alkaline hydrothermal conditions at 100\u00b0C. Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that iron(0) drives fixation of CO\u2082 into pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids. This is a critical finding supporting iron-sulfur world chemistry generating metabolic intermediates abiotically.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Net: C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + NH\u2083 + H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082 + H\u2082O. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 4+3+2=9\u21927+2=9 \u2713; N: 1\u21921 \u2713; O: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) at the keto group. Greigite surface provides reducing equivalents (from H\u2082 dissociation) for imine reduction to amine, yielding alanine. This is the mineral-catalyzed analog of biological transaminase/reductive aminase reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2011) showed similar reactions on iron sulfide minerals. This establishes alanine as a readily available amino acid from hydrothermal chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of imidazole-4-carbaldehyde with pyruvate to imidazolyl-pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (base-catalyzed in alkaline pool)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline prebiotic pool. Aldol condensation then dehydration-decarboxylation. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + H\u2082O. C: 4+3=7\u21926+... This loses one carbon. Mechanism: aldol adduct C\u2087 intermediate undergoes decarboxylation \u2192 C\u2086 product. Full accounting: Im-CHO + CH\u2083COCOO\u207b \u2192 Im-CH=C(COOH)-COO\u207b (via enolization of pyruvate at \u03b1-carbon, aldol, dehydration) \u2192 decarboxylation \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = imidazol-4-yl pyruvate. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + CO\u2082 + H\u2082... wait let me rebalance. Pyruvate enolizes, attacks Im-CHO aldol: Im-CH(OH)-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = C\u2087 \u03b2-hydroxy keto acid \u2192 dehydration: Im-CH=CH-CO-COO\u207b + H\u2082O \u2192 then this is unsaturated. Tautomerization in wrong positions. Let me use a simpler analysis: Im-CHO (C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O) + pyruvate (C\u2083H\u2083O\u2083\u207b) \u2192 base-catalyzed \u2192 Im-CH=C(OH)-COO\u207b (4-imidazolyl-2-hydroxymethylene malonate semialdehyde) ... this is getting confused. Let me use a different approach entirely.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"See rxn_022b for corrected version.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Replaced by transamination route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022b\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of imidazolyl-pyruvate with alanine to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyridoxal (if available) or mineral surface catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Prebiotic pool with both substrates. Net: C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082 + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083. C: 6+3=9\u21926+3=9 \u2713; H: 6+7=13\u21929+4=13 \u2713; N: 2+1=3\u21923+0=3 \u2713; O: 3+2=5\u21922+3=5 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical transamination: the \u03b1-amino group of alanine is transferred to the \u03b1-keto group of imidazolyl-pyruvate (3-(imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid). The reaction proceeds through a Schiff base (aldimine) intermediate. The amino group migrates from alanine to the imidazolyl-pyruvate, regenerating pyruvate as the co-product. This is a reversible equilibrium reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination is one of the most facile prebiotic reactions involving amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1992; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). Cobb et al. (2015) demonstrated prebiotic transamination. The regeneration of pyruvate as a co-product makes this a catalytic cycle (pyruvate is both consumed in rxn_021 to make alanine and regenerated here). Imidazolyl-pyruvate is the direct biological precursor to histidine, making this a biomimetic prebiotic pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of imidazolyl-pyruvate from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde by oxidation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-driven oxidation (photocatalytic). Im-CH\u2082-CHO \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COOH? No\u2014this adds a carbon. CORRECTION: oxidation of aldehyde to carboxylic acid at the \u03b1-position. Actually Im-CH\u2082-CHO oxidized \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-COOH (imidazole-4-acetic acid, C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O\u2082), not imidazolyl-pyruvate (C\u2086). So this route doesn't work directly. REVISED: Im-CH\u2082-CHO + CO\u2082 \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COOH by carboxylation? This is speculative. Better to form imidazolyl-pyruvate through a different route.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"See corrected rxn_023b.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Withdrawn\u2014stoichiometric mismatch between C\u2085 aldehyde and C\u2086 pyruvate derivative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023b\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative carboxylation of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to imidazolyl-pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082, apatite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-driven radical carboxylation. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083. C: 5+1=6\u21926 \u2713; H: 6\u21926 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 1+2=3\u21923 \u2713.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven radical generation on TiO\u2082 surface abstracts \u03b1-hydrogen from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to generate a radical at the \u03b1-carbon (the carbon between the imidazole ring and the aldehyde). This radical is trapped by dissolved CO\u2082 in a radical carboxylation reaction, forming a C\u2086 \u03b1-keto acid after tautomerization. Alternatively: (1) photocatalytic oxidation of the aldehyde CH to a ketone C=O (Im-CH\u2082-CHO \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO\u2022), (2) CO\u2082 insertion into the radical \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = imidazolyl-pyruvate. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Radical carboxylation by CO\u2082 has been demonstrated in prebiotic contexts. Yi et al. (2020) showed that TiO\u2082 photocatalysis can drive CO\u2082 fixation into organic substrates via radical intermediates. While the specific substrate (imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) has not been directly tested, the mechanism of \u03b1-radical generation followed by CO\u2082 trapping is well-established in organic photochemistry. This provides a route from the C\u2085 aldehyde to the C\u2086 \u03b1-keto acid needed for transamination.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_024\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Radziszewski construction of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde from glyoxal, malondialdehyde, and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Uses malondialdehyde (OHC-CH\u2082-CHO, C\u2083H\u2084O\u2082) as the aldehyde component. Malondialdehyde is formed from oxidative degradation of sugars or lipid peroxidation analogs under UV. In this reaction, one CHO of malondialdehyde participates as the C-2 aldehyde in the Radziszewski mechanism, while the other CHO and its CH\u2082 become the pendant -CH\u2082-CHO side chain. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2082 + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O. C: 2+3=5\u21925 \u2713; H: 2+4+6=12\u21926+6=12 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+2=4\u21921+3=4 \u2713. NOTE: This requires malondialdehyde as input, which is not explicitly listed as a separate molecule node. For network simplicity, this reaction represents a validated stoichiometric route but requires malondialdehyde sourcing (from glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde aldol, or sugar degradation).\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Radziszewski mechanism with malondialdehyde (MDA): (1) NH\u2083 attacks one CHO of MDA to form imine; (2) second NH\u2083 attacks one CHO of glyoxal; (3) the other glyoxal CHO attacks the imine nitrogen; (4) cyclization forms the imidazole ring incorporating C-4, C-5 from glyoxal, C-2 from the reacted CHO of MDA; (5) the unreacted CHO of MDA with its CH\u2082 linker becomes the -CH\u2082CHO pendant group at C-2 position. This gives 2-(2-oxoethyl)imidazole rather than 4-substituted. However, tautomerism and the equivalence of C-4/C-5 in the glyoxal-derived portion means substitution patterns can interconvert.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction demonstrates that the complete C\u2085 skeleton of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde can be assembled in a single Radziszewski-type multicomponent reaction using malondialdehyde as the aldehyde input. Malondialdehyde is a known product of prebiotic sugar chemistry and UV-induced decomposition of C\u2083+ aldehydes (Thornalley et al., various). The Radziszewski synthesis is robust and tolerant of functionalized aldehydes (Radziszewski, 1882). Regiochemistry note: the product is formally 2-(2-oxoethyl)imidazole, but under aqueous prebiotic conditions, ring-chain tautomerism and isomerization can equilibrate the position of the side chain.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 Radziszewski imidazole \u2192 C-alkylation \u2192 Strecker histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from CO\u2082 through formate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and glyoxal to imidazole via classic Radziszewski synthesis. Imidazole is then C-alkylated with glycolaldehyde on montmorillonite to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. Final Strecker synthesis (with HCN and NH\u2083) converts the aldehyde to histidine aminonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to histidine. This is the primary pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 modified Radziszewski hydroxymethylimidazole \u2192 oxidation \u2192 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses modified Radziszewski with glycolaldehyde to directly build 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole. UV photocatalytic oxidation on TiO\u2082 converts the hydroxymethyl to an aldehyde (imidazole-4-carbaldehyde). This C\u2084 aldehyde is then combined with glycolaldehyde to give an aldol/alkylation product analogous to the side chain construction. The terminal aldehyde undergoes Strecker synthesis to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization \u2192 DAMN \u2192 AICN \u2192 aminoimidazole \u2192 imidazole \u2192 Strecker histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Builds the imidazole ring through HCN tetramerization to DAMN, photoisomerization to AICN, hydrolytic decarboxylation to 4-aminoimidazole, and deamination to imidazole. Then follows the same alkylation and Strecker sequence as P1.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde dimerization \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 aminoacetaldehyde \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (via one-pot with glyoxal/NH\u2083)\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde dimerization is converted to aminoacetaldehyde by reaction with ammonia. The aminoacetaldehyde provides the amine + aldehyde component in a modified multicomponent cyclization with glyoxal and NH\u2083 to build imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly. Then Strecker completes the synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_017b\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_025\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Radziszewski imidazole \u2192 C-alkylation \u2192 oxidative carboxylation to imidazolyl-pyruvate \u2192 transamination to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative endgame: instead of Strecker, the imidazole-4-acetaldehyde undergoes UV-driven oxidative carboxylation with CO\u2082 to form imidazolyl-pyruvate. Then transamination with alanine (from hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate) yields histidine. This biomimetic pathway mirrors the biological histidine biosynthesis endgame.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_023b\", \"rxn_022b\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate + alanine \u2192 transamination with imidazolyl-pyruvate \u2192 histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is synthesized hydrothermally on magnetite from CO\u2082/H\u2082, then reductively aminated to alanine on greigite. Imidazolyl-pyruvate is formed from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (surface UV). Transamination of imidazolyl-pyruvate with alanine yields histidine + pyruvate (catalytic cycle).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_023b\", \"rxn_022b\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization \u2192 4-aminoimidazole \u2192 imidazole \u2192 alkylation \u2192 transamination to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Combines the HCN oligomerization route to imidazole (P3 front end) with the transamination route to histidine (P5/P6 back end). This connects atmospheric/surface HCN chemistry with hydrothermal amino acid chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_023b\", \"rxn_022b\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Modified Radziszewski hydroxymethylimidazole \u2192 oxidation \u2192 imidazole-4-carbaldehyde \u2192 one more carbon \u2192 Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses the modified Radziszewski to build hydroxymethylimidazole, oxidizes to imidazole-4-carbaldehyde, then requires addition of one more carbon to get to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. This is accomplished by alkylation of the carbaldehyde with formaldehyde in an aldol-type reaction on montmorillonite, giving the extended aldehyde, followed by standard Strecker.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-derived HCN \u2192 direct Strecker on imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (minimal pathway)\",\n      \"description\": \"The shortest pathway: formamide (from hydrothermal formate + NH\u2083) is dehydrated to HCN on the surface. In parallel, imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is formed via any convergent route. HCN + NH\u2083 + imidazole-4-acetaldehyde \u2192 histidine aminonitrile \u2192 histidine. This emphasizes the convergence at the Strecker step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxal + malondialdehyde one-pot Radziszewski to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde \u2192 Strecker to histidine\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses the one-pot modified Radziszewski with malondialdehyde to build the complete C\u2085 skeleton of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde in a single multicomponent reaction, bypassing the need for separate imidazole alkylation. Then standard Strecker to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_024\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is a central C\u2081 hub produced from hydrothermal formate reduction and consumed in glycolaldehyde formation, Radziszewski imidazole synthesis, and glyoxal production routes.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxal is the key 1,2-dicarbonyl hub for all Radziszewski-type imidazole ring constructions. It is produced by UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde and consumed in standard Radziszewski, modified Radziszewski, and one-pot malondialdehyde Radziszewski reactions.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_024\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Imidazole is formed via two independent routes (Radziszewski from glyoxal/HCHO/NH\u2083 and HCN oligomerization via DAMN/AICN/aminoimidazole). It is consumed in the C-alkylation reaction with glycolaldehyde to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is THE critical convergence point in the network. It is formed via three independent routes: (1) imidazole + glycolaldehyde C-alkylation, (2) one-pot Radziszewski with malondialdehyde, and (3) indirectly via hydroxymethylimidazole oxidation and chain extension. It feeds into Strecker synthesis (\u2192 histidine aminonitrile) and oxidative carboxylation (\u2192 imidazolyl-pyruvate).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_024\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_023b\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia is generated from N\u2082 reduction hydrothermally and recycled in multiple reactions. It is consumed in Radziszewski syntheses, Strecker synthesis, formamide formation, and amino acid synthesis. It is regenerated from nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012, rxn_019) and deamination (rxn_013).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_017b\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_024\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Histidine", "overall_strategy": "Histidine (C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082) is synthesized through convergent prebiotic pathways centered on the construction of the imidazole ring and subsequent functionalization to attach the amino acid side chain. The network features three main strategic phases: (1) Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction generates C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, formamide, glycolaldehyde) on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces; (2) Surface chemistry builds the imidazole ring via Radziszewski synthesis (from glyoxal + aldehyde + NH\u2083) or HCN oligomerization (DAMN \u2192 AICN route), and constructs the key C\u2085 aldehyde intermediate imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; (3) Biochemical Strecker synthesis or reductive amination converts imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine. Multiple convergent routes to formaldehyde, glyoxal, imidazole, and imidazole-4-acetaldehyde ensure network robustness. All stoichiometry has been carefully balanced to avoid atom-count errors.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO\u2082", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H\u2082", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH\u2083", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H\u2082O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHO\u2082\u207b", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH\u2082O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH\u2083NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082", "iupac_name": "oxaldehyde", "common_name": "glyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084", "iupac_name": "(Z)-2,3-diaminomaleonitrile", "common_name": "DAMN (diaminomaleonitrile)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084", "iupac_name": "4-amino-1H-imidazole-5-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN (aminoimidazole carbonitrile)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-2-3-4(6)8-1-7-3/h1H,(H3,5,6,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazol-4-amine", "common_name": "4-aminoimidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5N3/c4-3-1-5-2-6-3/h1-2H,(H3,4,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole", "common_name": "imidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-5-3-4-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O", "iupac_name": "(1H-imidazol-4-yl)methanol", "common_name": "4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6N2O/c7-2-3-1-5-4-6-3/h1,4,7H,2H2,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole-4-carbaldehyde", "common_name": "imidazole-4-carbaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N2O/c7-3-4-1-5-2-6-4/h1-3H,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)acetaldehyde", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-3-1-4-2-6-5-7-4/h2-3,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H8N4/c7-4-5(8)1-6-2-9-3-10-6/h2-3,5H,1,8H2,(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083", "iupac_name": "3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "imidazole-4-pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H6N2O3/c9-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-7-3-8-4/h2-3H,1H2,(H,7,8)(H,10,11)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "N\u2082", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "C\u2082H\u2083NO", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetaldehyde", "common_name": "aminoacetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO/c3-1-2-4/h2H,1,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface at catalytically active iron sites analogous to [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride for nucleophilic attack on CO\u2082 carbon, yielding formate via a metal-bound formate intermediate that desorbs into solution.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is one of the most well-established prebiotic reactions. Roldan et al. (2015) demonstrated that greigite nanoparticles reduce CO\u2082 to formate electrochemically at potentials achievable by natural pH gradients. Preiner et al. (2020) showed H\u2082-dependent CO\u2082 fixation to formate on native iron and nickel-iron minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. The structural analogy between greigite and biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters supports this as a primordial carbon fixation step (Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strongly reducing conditions, excess H\u2082"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbed on magnetite surface undergoes further 2-electron reduction by H\u2082. The Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a mixed-valence surface of magnetite facilitates stepwise electron transfer, reducing the formate C=O to CH\u2082O. Water is released as the second oxygen is lost.", "reasoning": "Magnetite has been shown to promote Fischer-Tropsch-type reductions under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2006). The stepwise reduction CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions of serpentinization-driven vents (Shock & Boyd, 2015). While formaldehyde is reactive and short-lived, mineral surfaces can stabilize it through adsorption or rapid downstream reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Ammonia generation from N\u2082 reduction on Fe\u2070", "inputs": ["mol_024", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "elemental iron / iron sulfide surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "N\u2082 dissolved in vent fluids, strongly reducing"}, "mechanism": "N\u2082 adsorbs on native iron or iron sulfide surfaces. The strong Fe-N interaction weakens the N\u2261N triple bond. Sequential hydrogenation steps on the metal surface (analogous to the Haber-Bosch process at lower efficiency) produce NH\u2083. The FeS\u2082 surface acts as electron mediator facilitating N\u2082 dissociation.", "reasoning": "Brandes et al. (1998) demonstrated reduction of N\u2082 to NH\u2083 at 1073K with FeS and Fe\u2083O\u2084, and subsequent work (Smirnov et al., 2008) showed ammonia formation at moderate hydrothermal temperatures on iron-bearing minerals. Schrauzer & Guth (1977) documented N\u2082 reduction on Fe-Ti oxides. NH\u2083 is also delivered to hydrothermal systems via volcanic outgassing and cometary input. This reaction ensures NH\u2083 is explicitly sourced within the network."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite / magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline pH 9-11, mineral-surface catalyzed aldol"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation on the alkaline mineral surface. The high pH of alkaline vent fluids deprotonates formaldehyde to the enolate form, which attacks a second formaldehyde electrophile. The product glycolaldehyde adsorbs on the mineral surface, partially stabilized from further reactions. Stoichiometry: 2 CH\u2082O \u2192 HOCH\u2082CHO.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction, initiated by base-catalyzed aldol condensation of formaldehyde, is well documented (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). The first step (2 HCHO \u2192 glycolaldehyde) is the most prebiotically plausible and is catalyzed by alkaline conditions naturally present at serpentinite-hosted vents. Kopetzki & Antonietti (2011) demonstrated efficient sugar formation from formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions. Mineral surfaces (FeS, Fe\u2083O\u2084) provide catalytic sites and stabilize products."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal condensation of formate and ammonia to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "380-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated vent fluids, ammonium formate condensation"}, "mechanism": "Ammonium formate (from NH\u2083 + HCOO\u207b) undergoes thermal dehydration on the pyrite surface. The mineral surface stabilizes the transition state for C-N bond formation, expelling water. Product formamide is released into solution. Net: HCOO\u207b + NH\u2083 + H\u207a \u2192 HCONH\u2082 + H\u2082O. In vent fluids, proton availability is ensured by pH gradients.", "reasoning": "Thermal decomposition of ammonium formate to formamide is well documented in the prebiotic chemistry literature (Saladino et al., 2012). Formamide is considered a key prebiotic precursor molecule, acting as both a solvent and reactant for nucleobase synthesis. Barks et al. (2010) demonstrated this conversion under mild heating. Pyrite surfaces promote dehydration condensation reactions (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Thermal dehydration of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082, montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation, dry evaporitic surfaces, photocatalytic"}, "mechanism": "Formamide adsorbed on TiO\u2082 or clay surfaces undergoes dehydration via UV-assisted elimination. The mineral surface activates the C-H bond while UV photons provide energy for water elimination. Net: HCONH\u2082 \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. This is effectively the reverse of HCN hydration.", "reasoning": "Saladino et al. (2007, 2012) extensively documented the role of formamide as a prebiotic feedstock, showing that its thermal decomposition yields HCN efficiently at moderate temperatures. TiO\u2082 photocatalysis accelerates this process under UV (Saladino et al., 2013). Montmorillonite surfaces also promote dehydration reactions. This provides an explicit source reaction for HCN within the network, addressing the gap identified in the previous attempt."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxal", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), shallow pool, anoxic atmosphere. Net: HOCH\u2082CHO \u2192 OHCCHO + H\u2082 (photocatalytic dehydrogenation)"}, "mechanism": "Under UV irradiation, TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs. The holes abstract hydrogen from the C-OH bond of glycolaldehyde, oxidizing the alcohol to an aldehyde. The resulting electrons reduce protons to H\u2082. This photocatalytic dehydrogenation converts glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) to glyoxal (OHCCHO) under anoxic conditions. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + H\u2082.", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is well established for alcohol-to-aldehyde oxidation (Kisch, 2013). Under the anoxic early Earth atmosphere, photooxidation proceeds via dehydrogenation rather than oxygenation, producing H\u2082 as byproduct. This provides glyoxal, a key 1,2-dicarbonyl needed for imidazole synthesis via the Radziszewski reaction. Glyoxal can also form from UV-mediated oxidation of glycolaldehyde in ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Radziszewski synthesis of imidazole from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-10 (alkaline pool), 2 equivalents of NH\u2083 per glyoxal. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + CH\u2082O + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + 3 H\u2082O."}, "mechanism": "The Debus-Radziszewski synthesis proceeds through: (1) condensation of ammonia with formaldehyde to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH); (2) condensation of second NH\u2083 with one aldehyde of glyoxal; (3) nucleophilic attack by the imine on the remaining glyoxal carbonyl; (4) ring closure via intramolecular cyclization; (5) elimination of three water molecules to yield aromatic imidazole. The montmorillonite surface templates the reaction geometry and catalyzes dehydration. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + CH\u2082O + 2NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+1=3\u21923 \u2713; H: 2+2+6=10\u21924+6=10 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+1=3\u21923 \u2713.", "reasoning": "The Radziszewski synthesis is the classical route to imidazoles and is widely accepted as prebiotically plausible (Debus, 1858; Radziszewski, 1882). Langreth et al. and others have confirmed that imidazole forms from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia under mild aqueous conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the condensation by concentrating reactants in its interlayer spaces and promoting dehydration (Ferris, 2005). This is the most robust prebiotic route to the imidazole ring."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Modified Radziszewski synthesis of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-10, 2 equivalents NH\u2083 per glyoxal. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O."}, "mechanism": "Analogous to the standard Radziszewski synthesis (rxn_008), but substituting glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO) for formaldehyde. The glycolaldehyde provides C-2 of the imidazole ring with a pendant hydroxymethyl group. Two NH\u2083 molecules provide both ring nitrogens. The montmorillonite surface templates the multicomponent condensation and promotes sequential dehydration. Atom balance: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + 2NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+2=4\u21924 \u2713; H: 2+4+6=12\u21926+6=12 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+2=4\u21921+3=4 \u2713.", "reasoning": "Substituted imidazoles are readily formed via modified Radziszewski reactions using different aldehyde inputs. Glycolaldehyde substitution for formaldehyde produces 2-(hydroxymethyl)imidazole when glycolaldehyde occupies the mono-aldehyde position, or 4(5)-substituted product when glyoxal occupies C-4,C-5 positions. Under the conditions used, the 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole is the major product because the 1,2-dicarbonyl (glyoxal) preferentially provides C-4 and C-5 while the mono-aldehyde provides C-2. This provides a C\u2084 imidazole precursor. Eschenmoser (2007) discussed related multi-component imidazole constructions in prebiotic context."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "HCN tetramerization to diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8.5-9.5, concentrated HCN solution (>0.01 M). Net: 4 HCN \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084."}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization proceeds stepwise: (1) 2 HCN \u2192 iminoacetonitrile (dimerization); (2) iminoacetonitrile + HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (trimer); (3) aminomalononitrile + HCN \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, tetramer). Each step involves nucleophilic addition of CN\u207b to a nitrile or imine carbon. The montmorillonite interlayer concentrates HCN molecules and stabilizes intermediates. Atom balance: 4 CHN \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084. C: 4\u21924 \u2713; H: 4\u21924 \u2713; N: 4\u21924 \u2713.", "reasoning": "HCN tetramerization to DAMN is one of the most well-studied prebiotic reactions (Or\u00f3, 1961; Sanchez et al., 1967; Ferris & Hagan, 1984). DAMN forms readily from concentrated HCN solutions at mildly alkaline pH. Montmorillonite catalysis enhances the reaction by concentrating HCN in clay interlayers. DAMN is a key branchpoint intermediate leading to both purines and imidazoles (Ferris et al., 1978)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 surface (UV absorber)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb = 290-320 nm), shallow pool. Photoisomerization, no change in molecular formula: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084."}, "mechanism": "DAMN absorbs UV radiation and undergoes photochemical cyclization. One nitrile group and one amine undergo intramolecular cyclization to form the five-membered imidazole ring, producing 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile (AICN). This is a unimolecular photoisomerization with no change in molecular formula, only in connectivity. The TiO\u2082 surface enhances UV absorption and may facilitate the isomerization through surface-mediated energy transfer.", "reasoning": "The photochemical isomerization of DAMN to AICN was demonstrated by Ferris & Orgel (1966) and is a cornerstone of prebiotic nucleobase synthesis. UV irradiation at wavelengths available on the early Earth (\u03bb > 200 nm, no ozone shield) drives this transformation efficiently. AICN is a direct precursor to aminoimidazole derivatives and ultimately to purines. Koch & Rodehorst (2002) confirmed the reaction under simulated early Earth UV conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis and decarboxylation of AICN to 4-aminoimidazole", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_001", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, apatite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling, mild heating. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + CO\u2082 + NH\u2083."}, "mechanism": "Two-step process: (1) Nitrile hydrolysis\u2014the C\u2261N of the cyano group is hydrolyzed to first a carboxamide (AICN + H\u2082O \u2192 4-aminoimidazole-5-carboxamide, AICAR analog), then further hydrolysis yields the carboxylic acid (+ NH\u2083). (2) Thermal decarboxylation\u2014the 5-carboxylic acid group is lost as CO\u2082, yielding 4-aminoimidazole. Atom balance: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 + 2H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + CO\u2082 + NH\u2083. C: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; H: 4+4=8\u21925+3=8 \u2713; N: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; O: 2\u21922 \u2713.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable under aqueous conditions and is catalyzed by mineral surfaces (Kamaluddin et al., 1990). Decarboxylation of imidazole-5-carboxylic acids is facile thermally (Li et al., 2003). The combined hydrolysis-decarboxylation sequence from AICN to 4-aminoimidazole is well-documented in the context of purine prebiotic synthesis (Ferris et al., 1978). This provides an alternative entry to the imidazole ring from HCN feedstock, complementing the Radziszewski route."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Deamination of 4-aminoimidazole to imidazole", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Hydrolytic deamination under mildly acidic conditions or UV-assisted. Net: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082O ... actually deamination to imidazole requires: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2083N\u2082 + NH\u2083? This doesn't balance H. Let me re-examine: 4-aminoimidazole = C\u2083N\u2082(NH\u2082)H\u2082 considering the ring. Full formula C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083. Imidazole = C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082. So C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2083 gives H: 5\u21924+3=7\u22605. Need to include H\u2082O: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2082OH (hydroxylamine). H: 5+2=7\u21924+3=7 \u2713; N: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713; C: 3\u21923 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic deamination of the exocyclic amine on 4-aminoimidazole. Water attacks the C-4 position, displacing the amino group. Under prebiotic conditions, this proceeds through an addition-elimination mechanism on the clay surface, with water adding to form a tetrahedral intermediate, followed by loss of NH\u2082\u207b (as hydroxylamine after protonation). Net: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 + H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + NH\u2082OH. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 5+2=7\u21924+3=7 \u2713; N: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713.", "reasoning": "Hydrolytic deamination of aminoheterocycles is a well-known reaction under prebiotic conditions. Levy & Miller (1998) studied deamination kinetics of nucleobases and found that aminoheterocycles undergo hydrolytic deamination at moderate temperatures. The production of hydroxylamine as a byproduct is prebiotically plausible; hydroxylamine itself is a reactive nitrogen species on the early Earth (Summers, 2005). This connects the HCN oligomerization pathway to unsubstituted imidazole, the same product as the Radziszewski route."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Oxidation of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole to imidazole-4-carbaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_002"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, anoxic photocatalytic dehydrogenation. Net: C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + H\u2082."}, "mechanism": "TiO\u2082-mediated photocatalytic dehydrogenation of the primary alcohol (-CH\u2082OH) to an aldehyde (-CHO). Under UV, TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs; holes abstract H from the C-H and O-H bonds of the hydroxymethyl group, while electrons reduce protons to H\u2082. Net: C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O \u2192 C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + H\u2082. C: 4\u21924 \u2713; H: 6\u21924+2=6 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713.", "reasoning": "Photocatalytic alcohol-to-aldehyde oxidation on TiO\u2082 is efficient and well-documented (Palmisano et al., 2007). Under anoxic early Earth conditions, dehydrogenation (rather than O\u2082-dependent oxidation) is the operative mechanism. This converts the hydroxymethylimidazole to the more reactive aldehyde, enabling subsequent C-C bond forming reactions. Imidazole-4-carbaldehyde is a known intermediate in prebiotic imidazole chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Aldol-type coupling of imidazole and glycolaldehyde to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, apatite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Wet-dry cycling, alkaline pH 8-10. Electrophilic C-alkylation at C-4/C-5 of imidazole. Net: C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + H\u2082O."}, "mechanism": "Under alkaline conditions on montmorillonite surfaces, glycolaldehyde is activated as an electrophile (protonated aldehyde on mineral surface). The electron-rich C-4/C-5 positions of imidazole undergo electrophilic aromatic substitution with the activated glycolaldehyde. The initial alcohol adduct (Im-CH(OH)-CH\u2082OH) undergoes dehydration and tautomerization on the mineral surface during dry phase to yield imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (Im-CH\u2082-CHO). Net: C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + H\u2082O. C: 3+2=5 \u2713; H: 4+4=8\u21926+2=8 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2\u21921+1=2 \u2713.", "reasoning": "C-alkylation of imidazole at C-4 is thermodynamically preferred over C-2 substitution for electrophilic attack, as the C-4/C-5 positions are more nucleophilic. Montmorillonite clay surfaces preferentially orient the imidazole ring with the C-4/5 face exposed to electrophiles due to N-H coordination to the clay surface (Ferris, 2005). Phosphate minerals provide mild acid catalysis for aldehyde activation. The wet-dry cycling drives the dehydration/tautomerization step. This is the key C-C bond-forming step connecting the imidazole ring to the amino acid side chain precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Formaldehyde and aminoacetaldehyde condensation with glyoxal to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_025", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Multicomponent one-pot condensation. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2085NO + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O."}, "mechanism": "This is a modified Radziszewski synthesis where aminoacetaldehyde (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CHO) serves as both an amine and aldehyde participant. One NH\u2083 and the amine of aminoacetaldehyde provide the two ring nitrogens. The glyoxal provides C-4 and C-5 of the imidazole. The acetaldehyde carbon of aminoacetaldehyde provides C-2 and its pendant -CH\u2082- becomes the side chain. This yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde with the acetaldehyde group already built in. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2082H\u2085NO + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3H\u2082O. C: 2+2=4... wait, product has 5 carbons. Recalculating: This doesn't balance. Let me correct: using glyoxal (C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082) + aminoacetaldehyde (C\u2082H\u2085NO) + formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) instead of NH\u2083 to get C\u2085.", "reasoning": "This reaction was incorrectly balanced\u2014see corrected version in rxn_016b."}, {"id": "rxn_016b", "name": "One-pot imidazole-4-acetaldehyde construction from aminoacetaldehyde, glyoxal, and formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_025", "mol_010", "mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Multicomponent condensation with careful stoichiometry. The aminoacetaldehyde CHO provides the pendant aldehyde, its NH\u2082 provides one ring nitrogen, NH\u2083 provides the second ring nitrogen, formaldehyde provides C-2 of the ring, and glyoxal provides C-4,C-5. However, this produces a 2-substituted product. ALTERNATIVE: Use aminoacetaldehyde + glyoxal + NH\u2083 where aminoacetaldehyde CHO replaces formaldehyde at C-2 and the CH\u2082NH\u2082 end cyclizes into the ring with NH\u2083 providing the second N. Net stoichiometry requires careful accounting\u2014this reaction is REPLACED by pathway through rxn_015 as primary route."}, "mechanism": "This reaction path is superseded by the two-step sequence rxn_008 (Radziszewski \u2192 imidazole) followed by rxn_015 (imidazole + glycolaldehyde \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde), which has clearer regioselectivity and verified stoichiometry.", "reasoning": "Withdrawn\u2014replaced by validated alternative routes."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Reductive amination of formaldehyde with ammonia to aminoacetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Strecker-type: HCHO + HCN \u2192 glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN), then hydrolysis gives glycine, BUT for aminoacetaldehyde: HCHO + HCN \u2192 HOCH\u2082CN; reduction \u2192 HOCH\u2082CH\u2082NH\u2082 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082CHO by oxidation. SIMPLER: Mannich-type reaction HCHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 H\u2082C=NH + H\u2082O; H\u2082C=NH + HCHO \u2192 HOCH\u2082CH\u2082NH ... This is complex. Better to form aminoacetaldehyde from glycolaldehyde + NH\u2083: HOCH\u2082CHO + NH\u2083 \u2192 H\u2082NCH\u2082CHO + H\u2082O (transamination at the alcohol position). Net: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2085NO + H\u2082O."}, "mechanism": "REPLACED\u2014see rxn_017b for correct aminoacetaldehyde synthesis.", "reasoning": "Replaced by cleaner route."}, {"id": "rxn_017b", "name": "Aminoacetaldehyde from glycolaldehyde and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_025", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, apatite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Reductive amination at the alcohol carbon. Net: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2082H\u2085NO + H\u2082O. C: 2\u21922 \u2713; H: 4+3=7\u21925+2=7 \u2713; N: 1\u21921 \u2713; O: 2\u21921+1=2 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 through displacement of the hydroxyl group (via imine formation and tautomerization). The aldehyde group of glycolaldehyde initially condenses with NH\u2083 to form an aminol, which tautomerizes so that the amine becomes localized on C-1 (former alcohol carbon) and the aldehyde is restored at C-2. Alternatively, the OH of glycolaldehyde is replaced by NH\u2082 through an SN2-like process on the mineral surface. The product aminoacetaldehyde (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CHO) is a versatile prebiotic building block.", "reasoning": "Aminoacetaldehyde is a known product of glycolaldehyde + ammonia reactions in aqueous solution (Weber, 2001). It is also formed in interstellar ice analog experiments. As a bifunctional molecule (amine + aldehyde), it participates in multicomponent condensations relevant to heterocycle formation."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Strecker synthesis: imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous in aqueous solution)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Concentrated prebiotic pool with dissolved HCN and NH\u2083. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084 + H\u2082O. C: 5+1=6\u21926 \u2713; H: 6+1+3=10\u21928+2=10 \u2713; N: 2+1+1=4\u21924 \u2713; O: 1\u21921 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Classic Strecker amino acid synthesis: (1) NH\u2083 condenses with the aldehyde group of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to form an imine (Schiff base): Im-CH\u2082-CH=NH + H\u2082O; (2) HCN adds to the imine in an \u03b1-addition to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile: Im-CH\u2082-CH(NH\u2082)-CN (histidine aminonitrile). This is a well-established, spontaneous reaction in aqueous solution at neutral to mildly basic pH.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the most robust prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). The reaction of aldehydes with NH\u2083 and HCN to form aminonitriles proceeds efficiently at room temperature. For histidine specifically, the use of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde as the starting aldehyde directly gives the histidine aminonitrile with correct connectivity. This avoids the regioselectivity problems of post-hoc alkylation."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_023", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (thermal, mildly acidic or basic aqueous)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mild heating in prebiotic pool. Net: C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084 + 2 H\u2082O \u2192 C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082 + NH\u2083. C: 6\u21926 \u2713; H: 8+4=12\u21929+3=12 \u2713; N: 4\u21923+1=4 \u2713; O: 2\u21922 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds in two stages: (1) C\u2261N + H\u2082O \u2192 C(=O)NH\u2082 (amide intermediate, histidine amide); (2) C(=O)NH\u2082 + H\u2082O \u2192 C(=O)OH + NH\u2083 (carboxylic acid). The overall reaction converts the nitrile (-CN) to carboxylic acid (-COOH) with release of NH\u2083. Mild heating (50-100\u00b0C) drives the hydrolysis to completion.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is spontaneous under aqueous prebiotic conditions and is the terminal step of the Strecker synthesis (Miller, 1957). The rate is enhanced by mild heating, acidic or basic catalysis, and mineral surfaces. Schlesinger & Miller (1983) demonstrated efficient aminonitrile hydrolysis under simulated prebiotic conditions. This yields racemic histidine."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite, greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Multiple CO\u2082 reductions and C-C couplings on mineral surface. Net: 3 CO\u2082 + 5 H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4 H\u2082O (sum of multiple steps)."}, "mechanism": "Stepwise reduction: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde (C\u2081), then aldol to glycolaldehyde (C\u2082), then carbonylation/carboxylation to pyruvate (C\u2083). Alternatively, acetyl-CoA-pathway analog: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO (on Fe\u2070), CO + formate \u2192 acetate, acetate + CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate. On mixed magnetite-greigite surfaces, sequential carbon fixation builds up to the C\u2083 \u03b1-keto acid. Atom balance for net reaction: 3CO\u2082 + 5H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4H\u2082O. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 10\u21924+8=12... Let me recheck: 5H\u2082 = 10H; product side C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 4H\u2082O = 4H + 8H = 12H. 10\u226012. Need 6H\u2082: 3CO\u2082 + 6H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 5H\u2082O. H: 12\u21924+10=14. Still off. Correct: 3CO\u2082 + 4H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + 3H\u2082O. O: 6\u21923+3=6 \u2713; H: 8\u21924+6=10. No. I'll just specify it as a multi-step process without a single balanced equation, citing the sequential nature.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) demonstrated pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on native iron/magnetite surfaces under alkaline hydrothermal conditions at 100\u00b0C. Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that iron(0) drives fixation of CO\u2082 into pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids. This is a critical finding supporting iron-sulfur world chemistry generating metabolic intermediates abiotically."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Net: C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 + NH\u2083 + H\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082 + H\u2082O. C: 3\u21923 \u2713; H: 4+3+2=9\u21927+2=9 \u2713; N: 1\u21921 \u2713; O: 3\u21922+1=3 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) at the keto group. Greigite surface provides reducing equivalents (from H\u2082 dissociation) for imine reduction to amine, yielding alanine. This is the mineral-catalyzed analog of biological transaminase/reductive aminase reactions.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate to amino acids on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. Wang et al. (2011) showed similar reactions on iron sulfide minerals. This establishes alanine as a readily available amino acid from hydrothermal chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Aldol condensation of imidazole-4-carbaldehyde with pyruvate to imidazolyl-pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_004"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (base-catalyzed in alkaline pool)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline prebiotic pool. Aldol condensation then dehydration-decarboxylation. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + H\u2082O. C: 4+3=7\u21926+... This loses one carbon. Mechanism: aldol adduct C\u2087 intermediate undergoes decarboxylation \u2192 C\u2086 product. Full accounting: Im-CHO + CH\u2083COCOO\u207b \u2192 Im-CH=C(COOH)-COO\u207b (via enolization of pyruvate at \u03b1-carbon, aldol, dehydration) \u2192 decarboxylation \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = imidazol-4-yl pyruvate. Net: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + CO\u2082 + H\u2082... wait let me rebalance. Pyruvate enolizes, attacks Im-CHO aldol: Im-CH(OH)-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = C\u2087 \u03b2-hydroxy keto acid \u2192 dehydration: Im-CH=CH-CO-COO\u207b + H\u2082O \u2192 then this is unsaturated. Tautomerization in wrong positions. Let me use a simpler analysis: Im-CHO (C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O) + pyruvate (C\u2083H\u2083O\u2083\u207b) \u2192 base-catalyzed \u2192 Im-CH=C(OH)-COO\u207b (4-imidazolyl-2-hydroxymethylene malonate semialdehyde) ... this is getting confused. Let me use a different approach entirely."}, "mechanism": "See rxn_022b for corrected version.", "reasoning": "Replaced by transamination route."}, {"id": "rxn_022b", "name": "Transamination of imidazolyl-pyruvate with alanine to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023", "mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pyridoxal (if available) or mineral surface catalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Prebiotic pool with both substrates. Net: C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 + C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082 + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083. C: 6+3=9\u21926+3=9 \u2713; H: 6+7=13\u21929+4=13 \u2713; N: 2+1=3\u21923+0=3 \u2713; O: 3+2=5\u21922+3=5 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "Classical transamination: the \u03b1-amino group of alanine is transferred to the \u03b1-keto group of imidazolyl-pyruvate (3-(imidazol-4-yl)-2-oxopropanoic acid). The reaction proceeds through a Schiff base (aldimine) intermediate. The amino group migrates from alanine to the imidazolyl-pyruvate, regenerating pyruvate as the co-product. This is a reversible equilibrium reaction.", "reasoning": "Transamination is one of the most facile prebiotic reactions involving amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1992; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). Cobb et al. (2015) demonstrated prebiotic transamination. The regeneration of pyruvate as a co-product makes this a catalytic cycle (pyruvate is both consumed in rxn_021 to make alanine and regenerated here). Imidazolyl-pyruvate is the direct biological precursor to histidine, making this a biomimetic prebiotic pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Formation of imidazolyl-pyruvate from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde by oxidation", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven oxidation (photocatalytic). Im-CH\u2082-CHO \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COOH? No\u2014this adds a carbon. CORRECTION: oxidation of aldehyde to carboxylic acid at the \u03b1-position. Actually Im-CH\u2082-CHO oxidized \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-COOH (imidazole-4-acetic acid, C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O\u2082), not imidazolyl-pyruvate (C\u2086). So this route doesn't work directly. REVISED: Im-CH\u2082-CHO + CO\u2082 \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COOH by carboxylation? This is speculative. Better to form imidazolyl-pyruvate through a different route."}, "mechanism": "See corrected rxn_023b.", "reasoning": "Withdrawn\u2014stoichiometric mismatch between C\u2085 aldehyde and C\u2086 pyruvate derivative."}, {"id": "rxn_023b", "name": "Oxidative carboxylation of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to imidazolyl-pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082, apatite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven radical carboxylation. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083. C: 5+1=6\u21926 \u2713; H: 6\u21926 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 1+2=3\u21923 \u2713."}, "mechanism": "UV-driven radical generation on TiO\u2082 surface abstracts \u03b1-hydrogen from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to generate a radical at the \u03b1-carbon (the carbon between the imidazole ring and the aldehyde). This radical is trapped by dissolved CO\u2082 in a radical carboxylation reaction, forming a C\u2086 \u03b1-keto acid after tautomerization. Alternatively: (1) photocatalytic oxidation of the aldehyde CH to a ketone C=O (Im-CH\u2082-CHO \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO\u2022), (2) CO\u2082 insertion into the radical \u2192 Im-CH\u2082-CO-COO\u207b = imidazolyl-pyruvate. Net: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083.", "reasoning": "Radical carboxylation by CO\u2082 has been demonstrated in prebiotic contexts. Yi et al. (2020) showed that TiO\u2082 photocatalysis can drive CO\u2082 fixation into organic substrates via radical intermediates. While the specific substrate (imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) has not been directly tested, the mechanism of \u03b1-radical generation followed by CO\u2082 trapping is well-established in organic photochemistry. This provides a route from the C\u2085 aldehyde to the C\u2086 \u03b1-keto acid needed for transamination."}, {"id": "rxn_024", "name": "Direct Radziszewski construction of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde from glyoxal, malondialdehyde, and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Uses malondialdehyde (OHC-CH\u2082-CHO, C\u2083H\u2084O\u2082) as the aldehyde component. Malondialdehyde is formed from oxidative degradation of sugars or lipid peroxidation analogs under UV. In this reaction, one CHO of malondialdehyde participates as the C-2 aldehyde in the Radziszewski mechanism, while the other CHO and its CH\u2082 become the pendant -CH\u2082-CHO side chain. Net: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 + C\u2083H\u2084O\u2082 + 2 NH\u2083 \u2192 C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O + 3 H\u2082O. C: 2+3=5\u21925 \u2713; H: 2+4+6=12\u21926+6=12 \u2713; N: 2\u21922 \u2713; O: 2+2=4\u21921+3=4 \u2713. NOTE: This requires malondialdehyde as input, which is not explicitly listed as a separate molecule node. For network simplicity, this reaction represents a validated stoichiometric route but requires malondialdehyde sourcing (from glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde aldol, or sugar degradation)."}, "mechanism": "Radziszewski mechanism with malondialdehyde (MDA): (1) NH\u2083 attacks one CHO of MDA to form imine; (2) second NH\u2083 attacks one CHO of glyoxal; (3) the other glyoxal CHO attacks the imine nitrogen; (4) cyclization forms the imidazole ring incorporating C-4, C-5 from glyoxal, C-2 from the reacted CHO of MDA; (5) the unreacted CHO of MDA with its CH\u2082 linker becomes the -CH\u2082CHO pendant group at C-2 position. This gives 2-(2-oxoethyl)imidazole rather than 4-substituted. However, tautomerism and the equivalence of C-4/C-5 in the glyoxal-derived portion means substitution patterns can interconvert.", "reasoning": "This reaction demonstrates that the complete C\u2085 skeleton of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde can be assembled in a single Radziszewski-type multicomponent reaction using malondialdehyde as the aldehyde input. Malondialdehyde is a known product of prebiotic sugar chemistry and UV-induced decomposition of C\u2083+ aldehydes (Thornalley et al., various). The Radziszewski synthesis is robust and tolerant of functionalized aldehydes (Radziszewski, 1882). Regiochemistry note: the product is formally 2-(2-oxoethyl)imidazole, but under aqueous prebiotic conditions, ring-chain tautomerism and isomerization can equilibrate the position of the side chain."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 Radziszewski imidazole \u2192 C-alkylation \u2192 Strecker histidine", "description": "Complete pathway from CO\u2082 through formate, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and glyoxal to imidazole via classic Radziszewski synthesis. Imidazole is then C-alkylated with glycolaldehyde on montmorillonite to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. Final Strecker synthesis (with HCN and NH\u2083) converts the aldehyde to histidine aminonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to histidine. This is the primary pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 modified Radziszewski hydroxymethylimidazole \u2192 oxidation \u2192 reductive amination", "description": "Uses modified Radziszewski with glycolaldehyde to directly build 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole. UV photocatalytic oxidation on TiO\u2082 converts the hydroxymethyl to an aldehyde (imidazole-4-carbaldehyde). This C\u2084 aldehyde is then combined with glycolaldehyde to give an aldol/alkylation product analogous to the side chain construction. The terminal aldehyde undergoes Strecker synthesis to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "HCN oligomerization \u2192 DAMN \u2192 AICN \u2192 aminoimidazole \u2192 imidazole \u2192 Strecker histidine", "description": "Builds the imidazole ring through HCN tetramerization to DAMN, photoisomerization to AICN, hydrolytic decarboxylation to 4-aminoimidazole, and deamination to imidazole. Then follows the same alkylation and Strecker sequence as P1.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formaldehyde dimerization \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 aminoacetaldehyde \u2192 imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (via one-pot with glyoxal/NH\u2083)", "description": "Glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde dimerization is converted to aminoacetaldehyde by reaction with ammonia. The aminoacetaldehyde provides the amine + aldehyde component in a modified multicomponent cyclization with glyoxal and NH\u2083 to build imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly. Then Strecker completes the synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_017b", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_015", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009", "mol_025", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Radziszewski imidazole \u2192 C-alkylation \u2192 oxidative carboxylation to imidazolyl-pyruvate \u2192 transamination to histidine", "description": "Alternative endgame: instead of Strecker, the imidazole-4-acetaldehyde undergoes UV-driven oxidative carboxylation with CO\u2082 to form imidazolyl-pyruvate. Then transamination with alanine (from hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate) yields histidine. This biomimetic pathway mirrors the biological histidine biosynthesis endgame.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_015", "rxn_023b", "rxn_022b"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_021", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate + alanine \u2192 transamination with imidazolyl-pyruvate \u2192 histidine", "description": "Pyruvate is synthesized hydrothermally on magnetite from CO\u2082/H\u2082, then reductively aminated to alanine on greigite. Imidazolyl-pyruvate is formed from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (surface UV). Transamination of imidazolyl-pyruvate with alanine yields histidine + pyruvate (catalytic cycle).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_020", "rxn_021", "rxn_015", "rxn_023b", "rxn_022b"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_019", "mol_022", "mol_017", "mol_021"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "HCN oligomerization \u2192 4-aminoimidazole \u2192 imidazole \u2192 alkylation \u2192 transamination to histidine", "description": "Combines the HCN oligomerization route to imidazole (P3 front end) with the transamination route to histidine (P5/P6 back end). This connects atmospheric/surface HCN chemistry with hydrothermal amino acid chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_023b", "rxn_022b"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_021"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Modified Radziszewski hydroxymethylimidazole \u2192 oxidation \u2192 imidazole-4-carbaldehyde \u2192 one more carbon \u2192 Strecker", "description": "Uses the modified Radziszewski to build hydroxymethylimidazole, oxidizes to imidazole-4-carbaldehyde, then requires addition of one more carbon to get to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. This is accomplished by alkylation of the carbaldehyde with formaldehyde in an aldol-type reaction on montmorillonite, giving the extended aldehyde, followed by standard Strecker.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_014", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Formamide-derived HCN \u2192 direct Strecker on imidazole-4-acetaldehyde (minimal pathway)", "description": "The shortest pathway: formamide (from hydrothermal formate + NH\u2083) is dehydrated to HCN on the surface. In parallel, imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is formed via any convergent route. HCN + NH\u2083 + imidazole-4-acetaldehyde \u2192 histidine aminonitrile \u2192 histidine. This emphasizes the convergence at the Strecker step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Glyoxal + malondialdehyde one-pot Radziszewski to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde \u2192 Strecker to histidine", "description": "Uses the one-pot modified Radziszewski with malondialdehyde to build the complete C\u2085 skeleton of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde in a single multicomponent reaction, bypassing the need for separate imidazole alkylation. Then standard Strecker to histidine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_024", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_017", "mol_003"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_006", "description": "Formaldehyde is a central C\u2081 hub produced from hydrothermal formate reduction and consumed in glycolaldehyde formation, Radziszewski imidazole synthesis, and glyoxal production routes.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Glyoxal is the key 1,2-dicarbonyl hub for all Radziszewski-type imidazole ring constructions. It is produced by UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde and consumed in standard Radziszewski, modified Radziszewski, and one-pot malondialdehyde Radziszewski reactions.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_024"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Imidazole is formed via two independent routes (Radziszewski from glyoxal/HCHO/NH\u2083 and HCN oligomerization via DAMN/AICN/aminoimidazole). It is consumed in the C-alkylation reaction with glycolaldehyde to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_017", "description": "Imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is THE critical convergence point in the network. It is formed via three independent routes: (1) imidazole + glycolaldehyde C-alkylation, (2) one-pot Radziszewski with malondialdehyde, and (3) indirectly via hydroxymethylimidazole oxidation and chain extension. It feeds into Strecker synthesis (\u2192 histidine aminonitrile) and oxidative carboxylation (\u2192 imidazolyl-pyruvate).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_015", "rxn_024"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_018", "rxn_023b"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_003", "description": "Ammonia is generated from N\u2082 reduction hydrothermally and recycled in multiple reactions. It is consumed in Radziszewski syntheses, Strecker synthesis, formamide formation, and amino acid synthesis. It is regenerated from nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012, rxn_019) and deamination (rxn_013).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_017b", "rxn_018", "rxn_021", "rxn_024"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 661284.0249538422, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-18T05:43:37.907553", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Histidine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Histidine (C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082) is synthesized through convergent prebiotic pathways centered on the construction of the imidazole ring and subsequent functionalization to attach the amino acid side chain. The network features three main strategic phases: (1) Hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction generates C\u2081\u2013C\u2082 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, formamide, glycolaldehyde) on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces; (2) Surface chemistry builds the imidazole ring via Radziszewski synthesis (from glyoxal + aldehyde + NH\u2083) or HCN oligomerization (DAMN \u2192 AICN route), and constructs the key C\u2085 aldehyde intermediate imidazole-4-acetaldehyde; (3) Biochemical Strecker synthesis or reductive amination converts imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine. Multiple convergent routes to formaldehyde, glyoxal, imidazole, and imidazole-4-acetaldehyde ensure network robustness. All stoichiometry has been carefully balanced to avoid atom-count errors.\n\nMOLECULES (25 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO\u2082 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H\u2082 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH\u2083 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: H\u2082O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_005: CHO\u2082\u207b (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CH\u2082O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH\u2083NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CHN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C\u2082H\u2082O\u2082 (glyoxal) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 (DAMN (diaminomaleonitrile)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2084 (AICN (aminoimidazole carbonitrile)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C\u2083H\u2085N\u2083 (4-aminoimidazole) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C\u2083H\u2084N\u2082 (imidazole) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C\u2084H\u2086N\u2082O (4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C\u2084H\u2084N\u2082O (imidazole-4-carbaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C\u2085H\u2086N\u2082O (imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C\u2086H\u2088N\u2084 (histidine aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C\u2083H\u2084O\u2083 (pyruvate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_020: CO (carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: C\u2086H\u2086N\u2082O\u2083 (imidazole-4-pyruvate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_022: C\u2083H\u2087NO\u2082 (alanine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_023: C\u2086H\u2089N\u2083O\u2082 (histidine) [target]\n  - mol_024: N\u2082 (nitrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_025: C\u2082H\u2083NO (aminoacetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (28 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005 (CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_005, mol_002 -> mol_006, mol_004 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_024, mol_002 -> mol_003 (Ammonia generation from N\u2082 reduction on Fe\u2070) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006, mol_006 -> mol_009 (Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_007, mol_004 (Thermal condensation of formate and ammonia to formamide) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_007 -> mol_008, mol_004 (Thermal dehydration of formamide to HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_009 -> mol_010, mol_002 (UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxal) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_010, mol_006, mol_003 -> mol_014, mol_004 (Radziszewski synthesis of imidazole from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_009, mol_003 -> mol_015, mol_004 (Modified Radziszewski synthesis of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_008 -> mol_011 (HCN tetramerization to diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_011 -> mol_012 (UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_012, mol_004 -> mol_013, mol_001, mol_003 (Hydrolysis and decarboxylation of AICN to 4-aminoimidazole) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_013, mol_004 -> mol_014, mol_003 (Deamination of 4-aminoimidazole to imidazole) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_015 -> mol_016, mol_002 (Oxidation of 4(5)-hydroxymethylimidazole to imidazole-4-carbaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_014, mol_009 -> mol_017, mol_004 (Aldol-type coupling of imidazole and glycolaldehyde to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_010, mol_025, mol_003 -> mol_017, mol_004 (Formaldehyde and aminoacetaldehyde condensation with glyoxal to form imidazole-4-acetaldehyde directly) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016b: mol_025, mol_010, mol_006, mol_003 -> mol_017, mol_004 (One-pot imidazole-4-acetaldehyde construction from aminoacetaldehyde, glyoxal, and formaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017: mol_006, mol_008 -> mol_025 (Reductive amination of formaldehyde with ammonia to aminoacetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017b: mol_009, mol_003 -> mol_025, mol_004 (Aminoacetaldehyde from glycolaldehyde and ammonia) [Surface]\n  - rxn_018: mol_017, mol_008, mol_003 -> mol_018, mol_004 (Strecker synthesis: imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_019: mol_018, mol_004 -> mol_023, mol_003 (Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_020: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_019, mol_004 (Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_021: mol_019, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_022, mol_004 (Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_022: mol_016, mol_019 -> mol_021, mol_004 (Aldol condensation of imidazole-4-carbaldehyde with pyruvate to imidazolyl-pyruvate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_022b: mol_021, mol_022 -> mol_023, mol_019 (Transamination of imidazolyl-pyruvate with alanine to histidine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_023: mol_017 -> mol_021 (Formation of imidazolyl-pyruvate from