"rxn_015", "rxn_023b", "rxn_022b"], "suggestions": ["If pursuing the transamination route, use rxn_022 (aldol of carbaldehyde + pyruvate) which is more plausible than oxidative carboxylation", "Investigate metal-ion catalyzed transamination as prebiotic alternative"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_020": 0.75, "rxn_021": 0.78, "rxn_022": 0.72, "rxn_022b": 0.65}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.7, "pathway_coherence": 0.73, "environmental_progression": 0.8, "target_achievement": 0.7, "overall_confidence": 0.72, "feedback": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis (rxn_020) is supported by Cody et al. work on FeS minerals. Reductive amination to alanine (rxn_021) is plausible. The aldol condensation of imidazole-4-carbaldehyde with pyruvate (rxn_022) is chemically reasonable. The transamination (rxn_022b) is the weakest link as it requires amino-group transfer catalysis. This pathway partially mimics the biosynthetic route (reverse of histidine degradation), which is appealing but requires establishment of the imidazole-4-carbaldehyde intermediate through other pathways, making it dependent on P2 or P8.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_022b"], "suggestions": ["Explore Cu\u00b2\u207a or Fe\u00b2\u207a catalyzed transamination as prebiotically plausible", "Ensure imidazole-4-carbaldehyde supply chain is robust"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_010": 0.88, "rxn_011": 0.87, "rxn_012": 0.7, "rxn_013": 0.65, "rxn_015": 0.52, "rxn_023b": 0.48, "rxn_022b": 0.65}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.62, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.78, "target_achievement": 0.6, "overall_confidence": 0.65, "feedback": "Combines the well-established HCN oligomerization front end with the problematic C-alkylation and transamination back end. Accumulates the weaknesses of both P3 and P5 without adding new strengths. The HCN-to-AICN portion is excellent; everything after imidazole formation is weak.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions